HOUSE BILL 877
F2 6lr3030
HB 920/25 – APP CF SB 628
By: Delegates Spiegel, Behler, Coley, Foley, Forbes, Kaiser, Lopez, Schindler,
Wims, and Wu
Introduced and read first time: February 4, 2026
Assigned to: Appropriations
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
House action: Adopted
Read second time: March 2, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Institutions of Postsecondary Education – Institutional Debt – Report
3 FOR the purpose of requiring institutions of postsecondary education to submit a report on
4 institutional debt to the Maryland Higher Education Commission each year
5 periodically beginning on or before a certain date; authorizing the Commission to
6 assess a civil penalty against an institution for failure to submit a report or
7 knowingly including inaccurate information in a report; establishing certain notice
8 and hearing procedures that the Commission must follow before assessing a civil
9 penalty against an institution requiring the Commission to develop and publish a
10 certain data dictionary on or before a certain date; and generally relating to
11 institutional debt reporting by institutions of postsecondary education.
12 BY adding to
13 Article – Education
14 Section 11–212
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
18 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
19 Article – Education
20 11–212.
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *hb0877*

2 HOUSE BILL 877
1 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
2 INDICATED.
3 (2) “ADMINISTRATIVE HOLD” MEANS ANY HOLD OR LIMITATION ON A
4 STUDENT’S ACCOUNT AT AN INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION THAT
5 PREVENTS THE STUDENT FROM ENROLLING IN COURSES, OBTAINING OR RESIDING
6 IN CAMPUS HOUSING, USING FACILITIES, OR OTHERWISE LIMITING THE STUDENT’S
7 ACCESS TO THE INSTITUTION’S FACILITIES OR RESOURCES.
8 (3) “CHARGE OFF” MEANS AN ACCOUNTING MECHANISM BY WHICH
9 AN INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION INDICATES IT NO LONGER
10 EXPECTS TO COLLECT AN INSTITUTIONAL DEBT, REGARDLESS OF WHETHER THE
11 INSTITUTION:
12 (I) REMOVES THE DEBT FROM ITS RECORDS;
13 (II) PURSUES THE STUDENT OWING THE DEBT;
14 (III) ACCEPTS PAYMENT FOR THE DEBT; OR
15 (IV) SELLS THE DEBT.
16 (4) “DEMOGRAPHIC CATEGORIES” MEANS THE FOLLOWING GROUPS
17 AND POPULATIONS:
18 (I) RACE;
19 (II) ETHNICITY;
20 (III) AGE;
21 (IV) GENDER;
22 (V) IN–STATE OR OUT–OF–STATE RESIDENCY;
23 (VI) ENROLLMENT STATUS; AND
24 (VII) DEGREE, CERTIFICATE, OR CREDENTIAL CONFERRED OR
25 PURSUED.

HOUSE BILL 877 3
1 (5) (I) “INSTITUTIONAL DEBT” MEANS AN EXTENSION OF CREDIT,
2 A DEBT, OR AN OBLIGATION OWED OR INCURRED BY A STUDENT, IN THE STUDENT’S
3 CAPACITY AS A STUDENT, TO AN INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION.
4 (II) “INSTITUTIONAL DEBT” INCLUDES CREDIT, DEBT, OR
5 OBLIGATION FOR:
6 1. TUITION CHARGES;
7 2. ROOM AND BOARD CHARGES; AND
8 3. FINES AND FEES.
9 (6) “NONJUDICIAL COLLECTION” MEANS COLLECTION OF
10 INSTITUTIONAL DEBT OWED BY A STUDENT TO A STATE AGENCY BY THE CENTRAL
11 COLLECTION UNIT IN THE DEPARTMENT OF BUDGET AND MANAGEMENT.
12 (7) “TUITION PAYMENT PLAN” MEANS AN AGREEMENT UNDER WHICH
13 AN INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION ALLOWS A STUDENT TO ENROLL
14 FOR AN ACADEMIC TERM AND DEFER PAYMENT OF PARTIAL OR FULL COSTS
15 ASSOCIATED WITH THAT TERM.
16 (8) “VOLUNTARY PAYMENT” MEANS A PAYMENT MADE BY A STUDENT
17 TO AN INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION TO PAY AN INSTITUTIONAL
18 DEBT, IN WHOLE OR IN PART, THAT WAS NOT MADE IN ACCORDANCE WITH A COURT
19 JUDGMENT OR A NONJUDICIAL COLLECTION.
20 (B) (1) ON OR BEFORE OCTOBER AUGUST 1, 2027, AND EACH OCTOBER
21 1 EVERY 2 YEARS THEREAFTER, AN INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION
22 SHALL SUBMIT TO THE COMMISSION A REPORT ON INSTITUTIONAL DEBT IN
23 ACCORDANCE WITH SUBSECTION (C) (B) OF THIS SECTION AND THE STANDARDS
24 ESTABLISHED BY THE DATA DICTIONARY UNDER SUBSECTION (D) OF THIS SECTION.
25 (2) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 1, 2027, AND EACH DECEMBER 1
26 EVERY 2 YEARS THEREAFTER, THE COMMISSION SHALL, IN ACCORDANCE WITH §
27 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, SUBMIT A REPORT TO THE GENERAL
28 ASSEMBLY SUMMARIZING THE REPORTS SUBMITTED TO THE COMMISSION BY
29 INSTITUTIONS OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION UNDER THIS SECTION.
30 (C) (B) THE REPORT REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (B)(1) (A)(1) OF
31 THIS SECTION SHALL INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION AS REFLECTED ON
32 THE LAST DAY OF THE PREVIOUS FISCAL YEAR:

4 HOUSE BILL 877
1 (1) TOTAL STUDENT ENROLLMENT, DISAGGREGATED BY
2 DEMOGRAPHIC CATEGORIES;
3 (2) TOTAL DOLLAR AMOUNT OF INSTITUTIONAL DEBT,
4 DISAGGREGATED BY:
5 (I) DEMOGRAPHIC CATEGORIES;
6 (II) NUMBER OF ENROLLED AND FORMER STUDENTS WHO OWE
7 INSTITUTIONAL DEBT;
8 (III) LENGTH OF TIME INSTITUTIONAL DEBT HAS BEEN OWED;
9 (IV) TYPE OF CHARGES FOR WHICH INSTITUTIONAL DEBT WAS
10 INCURRED;
11 (V) PERCENTAGE AND TOTAL NUMBER OF STUDENTS WITH
12 INSTITUTIONAL DEBT WHO RECEIVED A FEDERAL PELL GRANT; AND
13 (VI) DEBT AMOUNT THAT ACCRUED DURING THAT FISCAL YEAR
14 AND DEBT AMOUNT THAT ACCRUED BEFORE THAT FISCAL YEAR;
15 (3) STATUS AND COLLECTION OF INSTITUTIONAL DEBT, INCLUDING:
16 (I) PERCENTAGE AND TOTAL AMOUNT OF INSTITUTIONAL
17 DEBT HELD IN GOOD STANDING AND PAST DUE;
18 (II) NUMBER AND TOTAL AMOUNT OF INSTITUTIONAL DEBTS
19 UNDER TUITION PAYMENT PLANS, INCLUDING THE PERCENTAGE THAT ARE IN GOOD
20 STANDING OR PAST DUE;
21 (III) NUMBER AND TOTAL AMOUNT OF INSTITUTIONAL DEBTS
22 UNDER STUDENT LOANS OWED TO THE INSTITUTION, INCLUDING THE PERCENTAGE
23 THAT ARE IN GOOD STANDING AND PAST DUE;
24 (IV) NUMBER OF ENROLLED STUDENTS AND FORMER STUDENTS
25 WHO MADE VOLUNTARY PAYMENTS TO THE INSTITUTION DURING THAT FISCAL YEAR
26 AND THE TOTAL AMOUNT PAID;
27 (V) PERCENTAGE AND TOTAL AMOUNT OF INSTITUTIONAL
28 DEBT CHARGED OFF DURING THAT FISCAL YEAR;

HOUSE BILL 877 5
1 (VI) NUMBER OF STUDENT ACCOUNTS REPORTED TO A CREDIT
2 REPORTING AGENCY DURING THAT FISCAL YEAR;
3 (VII) PERCENTAGE AND NUMBER OF STUDENT ACCOUNTS
4 REFERRED TO A THIRD PARTY FOR DEBT COLLECTION OR SALE DURING THAT
5 FISCAL YEAR, INCLUDING DEBT COLLECTION AGENCIES, DEBT COLLECTORS, AND
6 DEBT BUYERS, AND THE TOTAL AMOUNT COLLECTED;
7 (VIII) PERCENTAGE AND NUMBER OF STUDENT ACCOUNTS
8 SUBJECT TO LITIGATION BY THE INSTITUTION DURING THAT FISCAL YEAR AND THE
9 TOTAL AMOUNT COLLECTED; AND
10 (IX) FOR PUBLIC INSTITUTIONS ONLY, PERCENTAGE AND
11 NUMBER OF STUDENT ACCOUNTS REFERRED TO NONJUDICIAL COLLECTION DURING
12 THAT FISCAL YEAR AND THE TOTAL AMOUNT COLLECTED;
13 (4) ADMINISTRATIVE HOLD ACTIONS BY THE INSTITUTION,
14 INCLUDING:
15 (I) NUMBER OF ENROLLED STUDENTS OR FORMER STUDENTS
16 WITH AN ADMINISTRATIVE HOLD DUE TO INSTITUTIONAL DEBT; AND
17 (II) NUMBER OF ENROLLED STUDENTS OR FORMER STUDENTS
18 WHO HAVE COMPLETED ALL REQUIRED COURSES BUT ON WHOM A DEGREE HAS NOT
19 BEEN CONFERRED DUE TO INSTITUTIONAL DEBT;
20 (5) A LIST OF PERSONS USED BY THE INSTITUTION FOR
21 INSTITUTIONAL DEBT–RELATED ACTIVITIES, INCLUDING ORIGINATING LOANS,
22 ESTABLISHING AND FACILITATING INSTALLMENT PLANS OR DEBT PAYMENT, AND
23 INITIATING LAWSUITS;
24 (6) A COPY OF ANY MODEL INSTRUMENT USED BY THE INSTITUTION
25 TO ESTABLISH AN INSTITUTIONAL DEBT, INCLUDING A PROMISSORY NOTE, AN
26 ENROLLMENT AGREEMENT, A TUITION PAYMENT PLAN, OR A CONTRACT;
27 (7) A SUMMARY OF AND CITATION TO THE INSTITUTION’S POLICIES
28 RELATING TO AN ENROLLED STUDENT’S FINANCIAL OBLIGATIONS, INCLUDING:
29 (I) TUITION PAYMENT PLANS;
30 (II) STUDENT LOANS OWED TO THE INSTITUTION;
31 (III) ADMINISTRATIVE HOLDS;

6 HOUSE BILL 877
1 (IV) DEBT COLLECTION; AND
2 (V) REPORTS TO CREDIT REPORTING AGENCIES; AND
3 (8) ANY OTHER INFORMATION THE COMMISSION DETERMINES IS
4 RELEVANT TO EVALUATING INSTITUTIONAL DEBTS.
5 (D) (C) NOTHING IN THIS SECTION MAY BE CONSTRUED TO REQUIRE AN
6 INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION TO REPORT PERSONAL IDENTIFYING
7 INFORMATION OF AN ENROLLED STUDENT OR A FORMER STUDENT.
8 (E) (D) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPHS (2) AND (3) OF THIS
9 SUBSECTION, THE COMMISSION MAY ASSESS A CIVIL PENALTY AGAINST AN
10 INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION IF THE INSTITUTION FAILS TO
11 SUBMIT A REPORT REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION OR
12 KNOWINGLY INCLUDES INACCURATE INFORMATION IN A REPORT AS DETERMINED
13 BY THE COMMISSION.
14 (2) (I) BEFORE ASSESSING A PENALTY, THE COMMISSION SHALL
15 SEND THE INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION A NOTICE OF THE
16 CHARGES AGAINST THE INSTITUTION AND GIVE THE INSTITUTION AN OPPORTUNITY
17 TO REQUEST A HEARING WITHIN 20 DAYS AFTER RECEIPT OF THE NOTICE.
18 (II) A NOTICE OF CHARGES UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS
19 PARAGRAPH SHALL:
20 1. DESCRIBE THE DEFICIENCIES IN THE REPORT; AND
21 2. DIRECT THE INSTITUTION TO CORRECT THE
22 DEFICIENCIES WITHIN 30 DAYS AFTER RECEIPT OF THE NOTICE.
23 (3) IF THE INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION REQUESTS
24 A HEARING WITHIN THE 20–DAY PERIOD:
25 (I) THE COMMISSION SHALL PROMPTLY HOLD A HEARING NOT
26 LATER THAN 60 DAYS AFTER RECEIPT OF THE REQUEST FOR A HEARING; AND
27 (II) THE INSTITUTION SHALL HAVE THE OPPORTUNITY TO BE
28 HEARD PUBLICLY BEFORE THE COMMISSION IN THE INSTITUTION’S OWN DEFENSE,
29 IN PERSON, AND BY COUNSEL.

HOUSE BILL 877 7
1 (4) IF THE COMMISSION DETERMINES THAT AN INSTITUTION OF
2 POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION FAILS TO SUBMIT A REPORT REQUIRED UNDER
3 SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION OR KNOWINGLY INCLUDES INACCURATE
4 INFORMATION IN A REPORT, THE COMMISSION MAY IMPOSE A CIVIL PENALTY NOT
5 EXCEEDING $10,000 FOR EACH VIOLATION THE COMMISSION SHALL DEVELOP AND
6 PUBLISH A DATA DICTIONARY THAT DEFINES THE TERMS, DATA ELEMENTS,
7 CLASSIFICATIONS, AND REPORTING CATEGORIES REQUIRED UNDER THIS SECTION.
8 (F) (E) THE COMMISSION SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS TO CARRY OUT
9 THIS SECTION.
10 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, on or before July 1, 2027, the
11 Maryland Higher Education Commission shall develop and publish the data dictionary
12 required under § 11–212(d) of the Education Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this Act.
13 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
14 July 1, 2026.
Approved:
